Description: Network Intercept is a privately held company dedicated to keeping your business safe from malicious intent on the Internet.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Los Angeles Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: Network Intercept is a privately held company dedicated to keeping your business safe from malicious intent on the Internet. Founded in 2008, the company created a series of products to protect businesses as well as individual home users from the known and unknown threats on the Internet. There are many solutions out there which claim to protect against the unknown, but only Network Intercept can do so without dependencies on signature updates, which saves significant time and money.  The flagship product, Interceptor.NET was built after company president Christopher Ciabarra experienced the full detonation of a zero-day attack on a corporate network while working for a major utility company. Ciabarra recognized the devastating impact on company productivity and understood how this could be avoided with the proper solution in place. Network Intercept was founded. Ciabarra worked with a team of security experts to develop a network solution that was easy and less expensive to maintain. This collaboration resulted in the creation of Interceptor.NET.

Description: Aviation Safety Resources designs, tests, and produces whole airframe parachute recovery systems to safely bring down an entire aircraft.
Headquarters Regions: Southern US
Full Description: Aviation Safety Resources designs, tests, and produces whole airframe parachute recovery systems to safely bring down an entire aircraft or vehicle and its occupants in the event of an in-air emergency.  ASR is focused its R&D on bringing a new dimension of safety to the rapidly developing Advanced Air Mobility (AAM) market.  AAM is quickly growing to a substantial market opportunity.  The emerging AAM vehicle market is projected to be $1.5 trillion with 3,000 Vertical Take-Off and Landing (VTOL) vehicles in operation by 2025.  This represents a $137M recovery system market within five years as the recovery system development will need to be ahead of vehicle designs.  ASR’s eXtreme Rapid Deployment (XRD) solution provides enhanced safety for the entire AAM concept for air transportation which is expected to have a high density of VTOL operations over heavily populated areas.  Not only can ASR solve the associated safety problem with recovery of a vehicle with no forward speed, but can ASR accomplish the objective within a compressed timeline driven by the current market developments.  ASRs Advanced XRD emergency recovery system for AAM directly aligns with the mission, goals and scope in addressing safety of non-conventional vertical lift configurations.
Industry Groups: Government and Military, Science and Engineering

Description: A Daughter's Comparison of her Parents' Last Journeys
Headquarters Regions: West Coast, Western US
Full Description: Sakre grew up in Southern California before moving north to attend the University of California in Berkley where she studied English, thinking she’d write the great American novel one day. Sakre married her college sweetheart, traveled to Austin, Texas for his doctorate, then to Seattle  for his first job. When they divorced, she returned to Austin, where she worked with children in psychological settings and completed a Masters in Special Education (Emotional Disturbance). She then moved East to Philadelphia to help a friend, eventually finding work in a clinic for emotionally disturbed children. After a year, she felt the pull to move back home to the West. For a number of years, she did various research projects before becoming the Executive Director of Project Care Interfaith Volunteer Caregivers in 1989 for seven years. After divorcing once again, Sakre continued as a researcher until following her heart to retire to the ocean in 2011. In 2017, she finished her second book about isolated Quakers in the  Northwest: Being Quaker… Where You Are. A third book, Final Choices: A Daughter’s Memoir Comparing her Parents’ Last Journeys, contrasts her mother’s doctor-directed struggle with terminal cancer with her father’s patient-directed choice to use the Death with Dignity Act when he was dying of a collapsed aorta valve, struggling to breathe. She currently lives part-time in Florence with her partner and part-time in Eugene to be near her daughters’ families.  She enjoys writing, traveling, reading, photography and, most important, spending time with her grandchildren.
